      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks, those are good. can u make the second one a bit more personal? the candidate was particularly strong in cloud architecture and they really seemed to connect with the engineering team. i want to acknowledge that specifically so it doesn't feel like a robot sent it, but i still need to keep it formal so there's no confusion about the decision.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's a smart move; acknowledging specific strengths makes a huge difference. You want to sound like a human who genuinely thought about their application, not just a HR bot.\n\nHere is a revised draft that incorporates that personal touch while maintaining professional distance. It's structured to praise the specific skills first, and then deliver the news gently.\n\n\"Dear [Candidate Name],\n\nThank you so much for your time and enthusiasm throughout the interview process for the Senior Developer role. We were particularly impressed with your deep knowledge in cloud architecture; your insights during our discussions with the engineering team were truly excellent. While we genuinely valued connecting with you, we have ultimately decided to move forward with another candidate whose profile was a slightly closer match for the immediate scope of this specific opening. We sincerely wish you the best of luck in finding a role where your talents can shine brightly.\n\nBest regards,\n\n[Your Name]\"\n\n***\n\n*Quick Note:* This version is strong because it validates their *specific* strength (cloud architecture) before delivering the 'no.' It feels tailored, which is much better than a generic rejection.\n\nIf you want to make it even *more* personal, you could add a line like, \"It was a pleasure",
